In his study of media coverage of three research fields, Schäfer (2009, p. 486) distinguishes four basic frames:


Scientific—including descriptions of scientific facts, evaluations of the scientific and medical implications of the research, and discussions about basic scientific norms and rights, such as freedom of research and research funding;

Political—microeconomic aspects (e.g., the research’s impact on companies and business) and macroeconomic aspects (e.g., impacts on stock markets or national economies);

Economic—including debates about the external (political and judicial) regulation of science and assessments of public participation in such regulation; and

Ethical, legal, and social (ELSI)—discussion about science’s view of human nature, possible discrimination based on the respective research, and property and patenting issues.
